Q: I'm using the DPMI version.  Each game allocates ALL of my extended memory
   even though only a small amount is actually used.

A: The runtime memory manager used by Trade Wars allocates all of the available
   extended memory by default.  To override this setting, you must specify
   an environment variable with the maximum extended memory.  Add this line
   either to your main AUTOEXEC.BAT or the batch file running the game:

   SET RTM=EXTMAX 1024

   This example specifies 1024K for each session.  This can be decreased
   depending on the memory use of your particular game.  20K sector games
   will use much of this amount, but a 1000 sector game will use much less.

   NOTE:  We recommend using this environment variable for not only TW2002.EXE,
   but TEDIT.EXE, EXTERN.EXE and NONPSERV.EXE.

Q: When I get a couple of games running simultaneously, the input and display
   seems to really bog down.

A: Trade Wars releases the timeslice multiple times during long processes
   like displaying ANSIs.  Depending on the timeslicing settings, the OS may
   be slow in returning the focus to a game after it has been released.  The
   result will be a significant slow-down in the game.  This problem seems
   to be worse for Win95 than WinNT.

   A new command line switch has been added (v3.09) to address this problem.
   You can set the switch to MULTITASK=NO to avoid relinquishing the timeslice
   during processing.  Setting to MULTITASK=YES will force the game to release
   the timeslice more frequently.  Win95/98/NT games will default to
   MULTITASK=NO and DOS and OS/2 games will default to MULTITASK=YES.

Q: Whenever EXTERN is running, active games slow to a crawl.

A: Starting with v3.09, EXTERN will frequently release its CPU time so that
   other active programs will be more responsive.

   This behavior can be controlled with the MULTITASK= switch.  The default
   value for the switch for all operating systems is YES.  If you are certain
   that no other programs will be running when EXTERN is active, or you
   find that other applications respond just fine while EXTERN is running, you
   can set MULTITASK=NO to significantly increase the speed of EXTERN processing.

Q: I can run the first game session fine but I can't start a second game.  It
   starts to run but then kicks me back out immediately.  It doesn't report
   any errors.

A: If you're capturing error output to a log file, be sure you're not trying
   to send the output to the same error log.  See "Common Technical Problems"
   above for a description of capturing error reports.



Q: I can run one or more game fine, but after a certain number of games are
   running I get an error trying to run an additional game.

A: This error could be "file not found" or something else.  The cause of this
   problem is usually that there aren't enough files allocated for DOS in the
   FILES= line of CONFIG.SYS.  Even though Windows allows many files to be
   open simultaneously, Trade Wars is a DOS program and is still restricted
   by the number of files specified in CONFIG.SYS.  Each game session currently
   requires about 15 file handles.

   We recommend you set at least FILES=120 in CONFIG.SYS.



Q: When running games on multiple machines that point to a shared data
   directory, one or more of the sessions can't receive messages.

A: Clock synchronization is crucial when running on more than one machine.
   Beginning with v3.05, a new global command has been added to synchronize
   the machines.  Here's what you should do.

     1:  Run a local session on each machine
     2:  From the main machine, press &.  This will synchronize all other
         machines running local sessions to the time of this machine.

   You can certainly do this manually, if you'd prefer.  The clocks need to
   be synchronized to within a second or two.



Q: Trade Wars seems to run fine in Local mode, but goes crazy for the remote
   callers?

A: TW2002 handles its own I/O.  Make sure that you are NOT using some other
   utility program or the BBS itself to handle the Modem I/O.  A program
   such as Gateway is not needed with TW2002.  Also, make sure you are using
   the door mode on your BBS that removes the BBS from memory.  This is the
   safest setting.



Q: No matter who runs the game, it always comes up as the same player or
   as me! (the sysop) what is happening?

A: TW2002 looks for your Door Interface file wherever you told it to.  If
   you have it pointing to the wrong one (not one the BBS makes whenever
   a user tries to run the door) then it will always try to run that
   configuration.  Also, if your Dos Environment variable TWNODE isn't
   set, it will default to Node 0 (local mode)



Q: Running TW2002 on WWIV, remote callers get double characters?

A: Under WWIV's Chainedit, you have Use Dos Interrupts set to "Yes".  Turn
   that setting off as you are asking both the BBS and Trade Wars to transmit
   characters to the remote user.



Q: When I run TW2002 I keep getting error codes 002 or 103.? Its never
   worked since I got it.

A: You never ran the INSTALL.BAT file when you first got the archive.  If you
   do not run this, then the appropriate data files were not created.



