Changes to TEDIT:

  Some new features have been added to TEDIT.  They are self-documenting.
  Also, the functionality of the TEDIT prompts has been revamped.  The range
  prompt bears mentioning.

  Range input text (Low to High) [Default] : _

  The Low and High values, if present, are boundaries for the input.  The
  default is the current value associated with the input, so that a <CR>
  will leave the field unchanged.

  A value can be entered (as long as it falls within the range), or one of
  two special keys may be used.

  < : Enter minimum value.  The prompt is terminated with the Low value
      entered as the result.  The , key will function identically.
  > : Enter maximum value.  The prompt is terminated with the High value
      entered as the result.  The . key will function identically.

Running Multiple TW Games:

  You can set up a main game directory and run multiple individual games from
  other subdirectories.  For example, you could create a directory C:\TW2002
  for the game files and then create three games running in directories
  C:\TW2002\GAME1, C:\TW2002\GAME2, and C:\TW2002\GAME3.  Any game specific
  data files will be created in the subdirectory for that specific game.
  To create these games, go into the main game directory, C:\TW2002, and
  run BIGBANG with the DATA= command pointing to the desired directory.
  For game 1, that would be

  CD \TW2002  
  BIGBANG DATA=C:\TW2002\GAME1

  This will generate the files TW*.DAT and TWINDEX.NDX, plus any Gold data
  files in the subdirectory GAME1\GOLD.

  The only data file that will not be generated in the individual game directory
  is TWNODE.DAT, the BBS node information file.  That file will always reside
  in the main executable directory.

  To run these individual games by BBS node, set the data path for each node.

  To run these games from any node, leave the BBS node data path set to
  default and pass the DATA= command to the game when it is called.  For
  example, you would run game 1 like this:

  TW2002 DATA=C:\TW2002\GAME1 or
  TEDIT DATA=C:\TW2002\GAME1 or
  EXTERN DATA=C:\TW2002\GAME1

  It is not necessary to change into the directory of either the game or
  the data files before running.  Simply execute the game with the full path
  and file name and it will change into the proper directory at execution.

  If no data path is specified in either the node data path or with a DATA=
  command, the game will look for the data files in the same directory as the
  game executables.


